{
  "family": "Wolff-Kishner Reduction",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCC(=O)CCC"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CCCCCC"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "NN",
      "[K+].[OH-]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction shows the reduction of a simple, acyclic, aliphatic ketone (3-hexanone) to its corresponding alkane (n-hexane). This is a classic textbook example of the Wolff-Kishner reduction, clearly demonstrating the C=O to CH2 transformation. The reagents, hydrazine (NN) and potassium hydroxide ([K+].[OH-]), are the standard reagents for this reaction. The substrate is simple and avoids other functional groups or aromatic rings that could cause ambiguity.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple aliphatic ketone, avoiding aromatic rings (which could trigger Friedel-Crafts or Clemmensen reduction queries) and other reactive functional groups. The transformation is a direct deoxygenation of a ketone to a methylene group, which is the defining feature of the Wolff-Kishner reduction, distinguishing it from other reductions or hydrazone-related reactions like the Shapiro or Bamford-Stevens reactions."
  }
}
